                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d97">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">500.A15a3/66: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Dawes</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Paraphrase]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1929-07-15T13:00:00+01:00"
                            >July 15, 1929—1 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received July 15—9:05 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>190. I received your telegrams Nos. 176 and 177, July 12, Saturday. I
                    communicated their contents to Mr. MacDonald while on a visit to Chequers
                    yesterday afternoon. The Prime Minister was greatly pleased and told me that in
                    order to properly express his appreciation of your action in the premises that
                    he wished to prepare a letter. This answer should be received by us very
                    shortly. Mr. MacDonald said <pb facs="0284" n="148" xml:id="pg_148"/> that your
                    response to the decision reached by him of postponing work on new cruisers was a
                    great contribution to the progress of the common cause for which we were
                    striving.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Dawes</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
